Sure! Here's an example that demonstrates how to correctly use the mappedBy attribute in Hibernate:

Consider two entity classes, `Customer` and `Order`, where one customer can have multiple orders. The relationship between these entities will be represented using a one-to-many association.

Customer.java:
```java
@Entity
@Table(name = "customers")
public class Customer {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;

    private String name;

    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "customer", cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
    private List<Order> orders = new ArrayList<>();

    // getters and setters
}
```

Order.java:
```java
@Entity
@Table(name = "orders")
public class Order {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;

    private String orderNumber;

    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "customer_id")
    private Customer customer;

    // getters and setters
}
```

In the `Customer` class, we use the `mappedBy` attribute in the `@OneToMany` annotation to indicate that the association is maintained by the `customer` field in the `Order` class. The cascade attribute is set to `CascadeType.ALL` to propagate save, update, and delete operations from a customer to its associated orders.

In the `Order` class, we use the `@ManyToOne` annotation to establish a many-to-one relationship with the `Customer` class. The `@JoinColumn` annotation specifies the foreign key column name in the `orders` table to maintain the association.

By using the `mappedBy` attribute, Hibernate will automatically handle the association between the `Customer` and `Order` classes, ensuring that any changes made to the `orders` list in the `Customer` class are properly propagated to the `customer` field in the `Order` class.

Hope this helps!

